  {
    "id": 63651,
    "text": "Dear wallet team, I have a manifest in which I create a proof of a resource from an account managed by my wallet and then use that proof to create another proof from an account that isn’t managed by any wallet, but is instead used more like a vault.\n\nThe wallet appears to reject the transaction because it detects that it does not control the other account and therefore assumes it should not call any methods on it. This is not what I would expect. While accounts are often tightly bound to wallets in practice, an account is still a component in its own right and does not need to be bound to a wallet at all.\n\nAs such, the assumption that a wallet can only call methods on accounts it controls is, in my opinion, incorrect. Is there any chance that the wallet could be made to behave less aggressively in these circumstances and allow for these types of manifests? I have a component deployed on Mainnet that used to work but is now affected by this issue.",
    "date": "2026-01-21T13:03:34.000Z",
    "sender": "6008290380",
    "senderName": "Mark - Radix Forms | The Radix Billboard",
    "hasMedia": false,
    "mediaType": null,
    "replyTo": null
  },
